This is a story about waiting, told in light and shadow.

====

**FADE IN:**

A ROCKY COASTLINE.

Waves crash against jagged rocks. A lighthouse stands alone against a grey sky.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
There are some places that exist outside of time. Not because they're forgotten, but because they choose to remember everything.

The beam of the lighthouse sweeps across the water. A small boat appears on the horizon.

NARRATOR (V.O.)(CONT'D)
The keeper had been here thirty years. Long enough to forget the sound of his own name.

INT. LIGHTHOUSE - LIVING QUARTERS - NIGHT

RONAN, 60s, weathered and kind-eyed, sits at a wooden table. A half-eaten meal. A radio crackles with static. He adjusts the dial.

RONAN
Come in, harbour. This is Fastnet.
(beat)
Harbour, do you read?

Nothing but static.

EXT. HARBOUR - DAWN

SAOIRSE, 30s, ties a boat to the dock. She carries a heavy rucksack and looks up at the lighthouse on the cliff above.

SAOIRSE
(to herself)
Still standing, then.

She begins the climb.

INT. LIGHTHOUSE - LIVING QUARTERS - CONTINUOUS

A knock at the door. Ronan doesn't move. Another knock, louder.

RONAN
(calling out)
It's open. It's always open.

The door swings wide. Saoirse stands in the frame, backlit by morning.

SAOIRSE
Da.

RONAN
~Is that my girl?
~Is that my Saoirse?
~Come in from the cold.

> **INTERMISSION** <

INT. LIGHTHOUSE - LAMP ROOM - NIGHT

Ronan and Saoirse stand beside the great lamp. The beam rotates slowly. The sea stretches black in every direction.

SAOIRSE
How long has the radio been out?

RONAN
(evasive)
A while.

SAOIRSE
How long, Da?

RONAN
(quietly)
Since your mother's funeral.

.LATER THAT NIGHT

They sit on the gallery, looking out. Stars.

SAOIRSE
You can't stay here forever.

RONAN
Watch me.

SAOIRSE
(gently)
That's what I'm afraid of.

CUT TO:

EXT. LIGHTHOUSE - DAWN

The beam goes dark. Morning light takes over. Saoirse walks to the boat, then stops and turns back.

- *"FOR SALE: LIGHTHOUSE. SOME ASSEMBLY REQUIRED."*

RONAN (O.S.)
Saoirse!

She turns.

RONAN (O.S.)(CONT'D)
Leave the keys on the table.

She smiles.

SAOIRSE
There are no keys, Da. There never were.

> _**THE END**_ <
